          </div>

          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">Benefits</span><h2>Benefits of Senior Citizen FDs</h2></div>
            <ul class="feature-list">
              <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Higher Interest Rate Premium</strong><p>Senior citizens earn 0.25%–0.50% more than regular FD rates. On a ₹50 lakh deposit, this translates to ₹12,500–₹25,000 extra income annually — a meaningful boost to retirement finances.</p></div></li>
              <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Higher TDS Exemption Threshold</strong><p>Senior citizens get TDS exemption up to ₹50,000 of annual interest (vs ₹40,000 for others). Submit Form 15H if total income is below the taxable limit to avoid any TDS deduction entirely.</p></div></li>
              <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Monthly Interest Payout Option</strong><p>Opt for non-cumulative FDs with monthly interest payout to create a regular income stream — perfect for meeting monthly living expenses in retirement without touching the principal.</p></div></li>
              <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Section 80TTB Tax Deduction</strong><p>Senior citizens can claim deduction up to ₹50,000 on interest income from bank deposits (FD, savings, RD) under Section 80TTB — effectively making the first ₹50,000 of interest income tax-free.</p></div></li>
              <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Premature Withdrawal Flexibility</strong><p>Most banks offer easier premature withdrawal terms for senior citizens with reduced or waived penalties. Some banks provide zero-penalty premature withdrawal for senior citizen FDs for emergencies.</p></div></li>
              <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Loan Against FD Facility</strong><p>Senior citizens can avail loans against their FDs at just 1%–2% above the FD rate. This provides emergency liquidity without breaking the deposit and losing the higher senior citizen rate.</p></div></li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">How to Apply</span><h2>How to Open a Senior Citizen FD</h2></div>
            <div class="steps-grid">
              <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">1</div><h3>Compare Senior Rates</h3><p>Review our rate table to find the best senior citizen FD rates across banks and NBFCs. Consider both the rate and the institution's safety profile for your retirement corpus.</p></div>
              <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">2</div><h3>Submit Age Proof</h3><p>Provide age proof (PAN, Aadhaar, or passport) confirming you are 60+ years. For super senior citizen rates (80+), additional verification may be required at some banks.</p></div>
              <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">3</div><h3>Choose Payout Option</h3><p>Select monthly, quarterly, or annual interest payout for regular income. Or choose cumulative option if you don't need current income and want maximum returns at maturity.</p></div>
              <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">4</div><h3>Submit Form 15H</h3><p>If your total income is below the taxable limit, submit Form 15H at the beginning of each financial year to prevent TDS deduction on your FD interest income.</p></div>
            </div>
          </div>

