  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Senior Citizen FDs</h2></div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What age qualifies for senior citizen FD rates?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>You must be 60 years or older to qualify for senior citizen FD rates at most banks. Some banks also offer super senior citizen rates for individuals aged 80 and above, with an additional 0.10%–0.25% premium. The age is verified using PAN card, Aadhaar, or date of birth on bank records at the time of FD opening.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Can a joint FD with a senior citizen get the higher rate?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Yes, but only if the senior citizen is the first (primary) holder of the FD. If the senior citizen is a joint holder but not the first holder, the regular rate will apply. Always ensure the senior citizen's name is listed as the primary account holder when opening the FD.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is Form 15H and when should I submit it?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Form 15H is a self-declaration for senior citizens (65+ for 15H, or 60+ who qualify) stating that their total income is below the taxable limit. Submit it at the beginning of each financial year (April) to all banks where you hold FDs. This prevents TDS deduction on interest income. You must submit a separate form for each bank.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is Section 80TTB and how does it benefit senior citizens?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Section 80TTB allows senior citizens (60+) to claim a deduction of up to ₹50,000 per financial year on interest income from deposits (savings accounts, FDs, RDs, and post office deposits). This is exclusive to senior citizens — regular taxpayers only get ₹10,000 deduction under Section 80TTA for savings account interest.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Which is better for seniors: Bank FD or NBFC FD?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Bank FDs offer DICGC insurance up to ₹5 lakh, while NBFC FDs are not insured but often offer 0.5%–1% higher rates. For the core retirement corpus, bank FDs provide maximum safety. A balanced approach is recommended: keep the bulk (70%–80%) in bank FDs within the DICGC limit and allocate a smaller portion to high-rated NBFC FDs (AAA-rated like Bajaj Finance) for higher returns.</p></div></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
